    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/hemolysis-invitro-comparison",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "In-vitro hemolysis index validation — absolute NIH values across 5 operating points",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/fda-pump-hemolysis-invitro",
      "description": "CFD-predicted normalized index of hemolysis (NIH) values were compared against in-vitro measurements obtained using the modified ASTM F1841 protocol at five operating conditions (2 L/min at 2500 RPM, 4 L/min at 3000 RPM, 4 L/min at 3500 RPM, 6 L/min at 3500 RPM, and 6 L/min at 4000 RPM). The Giersiepen power-law hemolysis model was applied to Lagrangian particle trajectories seeded uniformly at the inlet. A total of 50 000 particles were tracked per operating point. Monte Carlo uncertainty quantification was performed by sampling the three Giersiepen model constants (alpha, beta, C) from literature-derived distributions across 1000 ensemble members. Predicted NIH values fell within ±18% of measured values at four of five operating points; the 6 L/min / 4000 RPM point showed a 31% over-prediction attributed to unresolved tip-leakage vortex dynamics. The ensemble 95th-percentile NIH remained below the clinical threshold of 0.01 g/100 L at all five points, supporting the acceptance decision. Experimental uncertainty in the in-vitro measurements was estimated at ±12% (95% CI) based on repeat runs across three pump specimens. All CFD runs used ANSYS Fluent 2023 R1 on the university HPC cluster; mesh independence was confirmed at 14.2 million polyhedral cells. This result constitutes the primary hemolysis validation evidence for COU2."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/pressure-head-comparison",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Pressure-head versus flow curve validation",
      "comparedAgainst": "https://uofa.net/synth/data/fda-pump-hemolysis-invitro",
      "prov:wasGeneratedBy": "https://uofa.net/synth/activity/pressure-head-validation-2024q4"
    }
  ],
